======================================================================
CAPACITY-MATCHING HYPOTHESIS CHECK
======================================================================

Hypothesis: smaller LSTMs benefit more from mechanistic features, so
removing them (NO_STATIC_MECH, PURE_ML) should hurt small models more
than large ones. Look for a monotonically decreasing degradation as
LSTM size grows.

NO_STATIC_MECH:
   units=  4: degradation =  +4.64% ą  5.13%, MAE = 0.3677
   units=  8: degradation =  +3.06% ą  8.23%, MAE = 0.3832
   units= 16: degradation =  +1.96% ą  4.88%, MAE = 0.3893
   units= 32: degradation =  -1.35% ą  5.45%, MAE = 0.4001
   Trend across sizes: monotonically decreasing (consistent with hypothesis)

PURE_ML:
   units=  4: degradation = +10.43% ą 10.85%, MAE = 0.3880
   units=  8: degradation =  +4.49% ą 13.50%, MAE = 0.3885
   units= 16: degradation =  +0.67% ą  5.77%, MAE = 0.3844
   units= 32: degradation =  +0.62% ą  8.57%, MAE = 0.4081
   Trend across sizes: monotonically decreasing (consistent with hypothesis)

